Exploratory Analysis

  • Individual features and their properties and distributions
  • Basic relationships and correlation between individual features
  • PCA and basic clustering of the dataset

default_blue = sns.color_palette()[0]

for i, variable in enumerate(source_df.drop("quality_over_7_or_more", axis=1).columns):
    sns.kdeplot(data=source_df, x=variable, ax=axes[i, 0], fill=True)
    axes[i, 0].set_ylabel(variable.title())
    axes[i, 0].set_yticks([])
    axes[i, 0].set_xlabel("")

    mean_val = source_df[variable].mean()
    std_dev = source_df[variable].std()

    stat, p_val = normaltest(source_df[variable])
    normality = "Normal" if p_val > 0.05 else "Not normal"
    axes[i, 0].text(
        x=0.95,
        y=0.8,
        s=f"{normality}\nP-val: {round(p_val, 3)}\nMean: {mean_val:.2f}\nStd Dev: {std_dev:.2f}",
        ha="right",
        va="center",
        transform=axes[i, 0].transAxes,
        fontsize=9,
        bbox=dict(boxstyle="round,pad=0.3", edgecolor="blue", facecolor="white"),
    )

    sns.boxplot(
        x=source_df_scaled[variable],
        ax=axes[i, 1],
        fliersize=0.5,
        boxprops=dict(facecolor=default_blue + (0.3,)),
        whiskerprops=dict(color=default_blue),
        capprops=dict(color=default_blue),
        medianprops=dict(color="white"),

    axes[i, 1].set_xlim(-4, 4)

    skewness = skew(source_df[variable])
    excess_kurtosis = kurtosis(source_df[variable])

    axes[i, 1].text(

None of the variables are normally distributed.

Kurtosis how the tails of a distribution differ from the normal distribution. We can see that some variables:

  • Residual Sugar
  • Chlorides
  • Sulphates have very high values. This indicates a high likelihood of outliers, as more data points are in the extremes of the distribution.

On the other hand features which have low kurtosis is closer to a normal distribution (with negative values indicatates less outlier than a normal distribution).

All the features are also skewed to the right to a smaller or bigger extent. It means that the bulk of the data for each feature concentrated on the lower end of the scale, with a tail that stretches towards higher values. Intuitively it makes sense e.g.:

  • Residual sugar, most wines might have low sugar levels (dry wines), but a few wines (like desert wines) have very high sugar levels. This creates a long tail to the right while most data is clustered on the left (lower sugar levels). This is especially exacerbated by the fact that all the wines in the dataset come from the "Vinho Verde" region in Portugal were generally only dry wines are produced.
  • Similar reasoning can be applied to alcohol content. Most wines might have a moderate alcohol level, but a few might have unusually high alcohol levels, again stretching the tail to the right.

There seems to be no correlation between sugar and alcohol content which is something we would not expect if we were analyzing a broad selection of wines sampled globally. However, the dataset is restricted to wines from the 'Vinho Verde' region where sweet wines (as in most of Portugal) are not very popular, so it's not that surprising (sweet wines can have more than 30g\L of sugar and there are no such wines at all in the dataset).

There seems to be a significant statistical relationship between alcohol content and quality. However, it seems to be the strongest for high quality wines as the importance of alcohol for quality seems to decreases for lower quality wines. In fact between quality '4' and '5' the correlation is negative.

Generally relatively cheap wines for everyday consumption tend to be weaker. Based on the data we can see that while lower quality wines still might have a high alcohol content it's less likely that a weaker wines might have received a high quality score.

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

vmin = 0.1
corr = source_df.corr(method="spearman")
corr = corr.map(lambda v: 0 if (v < vmin and v > (-1 * vmin)) else v)

mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr, dtype=bool))

f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(11, 9))
cmap = sns.color_palette("ch:s=-.2,r=.6", as_cmap=True)

cmap.set_under("grey", vmin)


def annot(corr_val):
    if corr_val > 0.3:
        return f"{corr_val:.2f}"
    else:
        return ""


sns.heatmap(
    corr,
    mask=mask,
    cmap=cmap,
    vmax=1,
    vmin=vmin,
    annot=np.vectorize(annot)(corr),
    fmt="",
    annot_kws={"size": 12},
    square=True,
    linewidths=0.5,
    cbar_kws={"shrink": 0.5},
)

plt.suptitle("Correlation Between Wine Attributes", fontsize=16)

import shared as utils

source_df_qual = source_df.copy()
source_df_qual["quality_binary"] = source_df_qual["quality"].map(utils.bin_quality)

corr = abs(source_df_qual.drop("quality_binary", axis=1).corr(method="spearman"))

pairs_to_plot = []
for i in range(len(corr.columns)):
    for j in range(i + 1, len(corr.columns)):
        if abs(corr.iloc[i, j]) > 0.3:
            pairs_to_plot.append((corr.columns[i], corr.columns[j]))

n = len(pairs_to_plot)
ncols = int(np.ceil(np.sqrt(n)))
nrows = int(np.ceil(n / ncols))

fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows, ncols=ncols, figsize=(4 * ncols, 4 * nrows))

axes = axes.flatten()

for i, pair in enumerate(pairs_to_plot):
    sns.scatterplot(
        x=pair[0],
        y=pair[1],
        hue="quality_binary",
        data=source_df_qual,
        ax=axes[i],
        legend=False,
    )
    sns.regplot(
        x=pair[0],
        y=pair[1],
        data=source_df,
        ax=axes[i],
        scatter=False,
        color="grey",
        line_kws={"alpha": 0.5},
    )

    corr_coeff, p_value = stats.spearmanr(
        source_df_qual[pair[0]], source_df_qual[pair[1]]
    )
    r_squared = corr_coeff**2
    significance = "sig." if p_value < 0.05 else ""
    axes[i].annotate(
        f"R = {r_squared:.2f}\nP-v = {p_value:.2f}",
        xy=(0.05, 0.95),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
        ha="left",
        va="top",
        bbox=dict(boxstyle="round,pad=0.25", alpha=0.5),
    )

for i in range(n, nrows * ncols):
    axes[i].set_visible(False)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.suptitle(
    "Plots of Correlated (>.3) Variable Pairs (Quality > 6 Marked)", fontsize=16, y=1.02
)

plt.show()

t-SNE groups data points based on how close they are to each other in the original high-dimensional space, forming clear clusters, it's a non-linear algorithm, which preserves local relationships and is better for visualizing clusters in high-dimensional data. (PCA is a linear algorithm that reduces dimensionality by preserving maximum variance and feature correlation).

In theory we would expect that t-SNE would likely be more effective for visualizing clusters. Which we is something we'll try to do in our next step.

Clustering

If we were solving a real world problem, like for instance building a model/system which would allow wine merchants and distributors to select wines based on their chemical properties (to prioritize higher quality wines) in addition to finding identifying relationships between quality and other attributes (and building more complex models which we'll do in the 'Models' notebook we should consider another problem:

Improved: If we were solving a real-world problem, such as creating a model/system to help wine merchants and distributors select which wines to stock based on chemical properties (using quality ratings assigned to similar wines previously) we might run into this problem:

  • A focus on quality alone may overlook consumer preferences for specific types of wine.

e.g. if it turns out that non-sweet, higher acidity wines with a high alcohol content tend to receive higher 'quality' only focusing on quality might not be the best approach. Consumers with a preference for these wines are likely to statisfied with us stocking just 2-3 brands of these wines. Meanwhile, those who prefer less acidic, lower alcohol wines would have limited choices.

Therefore, if a merchant uses our model or system to select a fixed number of wines, we should also aim to maximize the variety of that selection. To achieve this, we could cluster the dataset based on chemical properties. For example, if we find three distinct clusters in the dataset, a merchant wishing to order 15 new wines could choose 5 of the highest quality from each cluster. This approach avoids merely selecting the 15 wines expected to have the highest quality rating based on past data.

The find_optimal_clusters functions searchs for "best" candidate clusters using a weighted combined score of 'Silhouette', 'Calinski harabasz', 'Davies bouldin' metrics. Using a combination of clustering methods:

  • Hierarchical
    • parameters: cutoff value
  • DBSCAN
    • parameters: eps, min_samples

And a combination of prepreprocessing techniques:

  • standardized data
  • PCA (3..10 components)
  • t-SNE (2 or 3 components)

While rejecting candidates where the smallest cluster has less than 100 items.

Best Clusters: Weights: Silhouette = 40% Calinski Harabasz = 20% Davies Bouldin = 20%

from IPython.display import Markdown

importance_order = [
    "quality",

    "sulphates",
    "volatile acidity",

overall_stats = source_df_cluster.describe()

clusters = source_df_cluster["cluster"].unique()

cluster_desc = {
    2: "These wines are characterized by a slightly lower citric acid and alcohol content, offering a subtly smoother and lighter taste profile",
    3: "This selection stands out for its notably lower volatile acidity and higher citric acid and alcohol levels, providing a robust flavor with a distinctive sharpness",
    5: "Wines in this cluster are distinguished by their higher residual sugar and chloride content, offering a sweeter, more pronounced taste with a hint of saltiness",
    1: "Featuring a lower level of fixed acidity and citric acid, these wines are milder and less acidic, ideal for those who enjoy a softer palate",
    4: "This group is unique for its significantly higher fixed acidity and density, resulting in wines that are more full-bodied and intense",
}
for cluster in clusters:
    _df = source_df_cluster[source_df_cluster["cluster"] == cluster]
    cluster_stats = _df.describe()
    overall_std = source_df_cluster.std()
    overall_mean = source_df_cluster.mean()
    n_cluster = len(_df)
    n_overall = len(source_df_cluster)

    markdown_text = f"\nCluster {cluster}\n\n- n: {len(_df)}\n"
    markdown_text += f"_{cluster_desc[cluster]}_\n\n"
    markdown_text += "```\n"

    for col in _df.columns:
        if col not in ["cluster", "", "quality_over_7_or_more"]:
            u_stat, p_val = mannwhitneyu(
                _df[col], source_df_cluster[col], alternative="two-sided"
            )
            mean_diff = cluster_stats.loc["mean", col] - overall_stats.loc["mean", col]

            mean_z_score = mean_diff / overall_std[col]
            pooled_std = np.sqrt(
                (
                    (n_cluster - 1) * np.square(_df[col].std())
                    + (n_overall - 1) * np.square(overall_std[col])
                )
                / (n_cluster + n_overall - 2)
            )

            cohen_d = mean_diff / pooled_std

            if p_val < 0.05 and abs(cohen_d) > 0.5:
                median_diff = (
                    cluster_stats.loc["50%", col] - overall_stats.loc["50%", col]
                )
                q1_diff = cluster_stats.loc["25%", col] - overall_stats.loc["25%", col]
                q3_diff = cluster_stats.loc["75%", col] - overall_stats.loc["75%", col]
                q1_z_score = q1_diff / overall_std[col]
                q3_z_score = q3_diff / overall_std[col]

                markdown_text += f"- {col.title()}:\n"
                markdown_text += (
                    f"  P-val: {round(p_val, 2)} < 0.05 (u_stat={round(u_stat)})\n"
                )

                markdown_text += f"  mean: {_df[col].mean():.4f} ({mean_diff:+.4f} | z={mean_z_score:+.2f} | Cohen's d*={cohen_d:+.2f})\n"

                markdown_text += f"  median: {_df[col].median():.4f}\n"
                markdown_text += f"  Q1: {_df[col].quantile(0.25):.4f} ({q1_diff:+.4f} | z={q1_z_score:+.2f})\n"
                markdown_text += f"  Q3: {_df[col].quantile(0.75):.4f} ({q3_diff:+.4f} | z={q3_z_score:+.2f})\n\n"

    markdown_text += "```"

    display(Markdown(markdown_text))

display(
    Markdown(
        """
\* Cohen's d measures the effect size between two groups using the pooled standard deviation, a combined measure of both groups' variability. Unlike the Z-Score, which compares individual scores to a group average, Cohen's d is better for comparing two distinct groups because it specifically addresses their relative difference in the context of their combined variability
"""
    )
)
